Britain has denied visas to two outspoken  Chinese dissidents in the United States who had planned to visit Hong Kong for  a seminar, local newspapers said Saturday.
Liu Binyan and Ruan Ming were quoted as saying that the British consulate  in New York had denied them visas to Hong Kong on instructions from the  British colony's immigration department.
They were to attend a seminar in Hong Kong next week, coinciding with the  fifth anniversary of the Tiananmen Square massacre.
Liu was known for exposing government corruption when a senior reporter at  the People's Daily newspaper. Ruan was secretary to former Chinese Communist  Party general secretary Hu Yaobang.
A government spokesman refused to comment Saturday on the visa refusals,  saying it cannot discuss individual cases.
